\frac{d}{dy} $$\nWhile this simplifies the form, it does not remove the topological feature of the domain: the real line is punctured at $y\u003d0$.\n\n### 5. Incompleteness of the Flow\nFor a first-order operator $-i v(y) \\frac{d}{dy}$ to be essentially self-adjoint, the classical trajectories generated by the velocity field $v(y)$ must act on the full real line without reaching a boundary in finite time.\nHere, the velocity is constant ($v \\propto k_z$). A particle starting at $y_0$ follows the path:\n$$ y(t) \u003d y_0 + v t $$\nThis particle will reach the singularity $y\u003d0$ in finite time $t \u003d -y_0/v$.\n\nBecause the \"particle\" (probability current) hits the hole at $y\u003d0$ and disappears from the domain in finite time, the operator is not essentially self-adjoint.\n*   In technical terms, the operator has **non-zero deficiency indices** (specifically $(1,1)$ for the combined domain).\n*   To make it self-adjoint, one must specify a **boundary condition** at $y\u003d0$ that connects the wavefunction at $y\u003d0^-$ to $y\u003d0^+$ (e.g., a phase shift describing how the particle passes through the singularity).\n*   Since there are infinitely many possible boundary conditions (choices of phase), the operator is not *essentially* self-adjoint (which requires a unique extension).\n\n**Conclusion:** The Hamiltonian is **not essentially self-adjoint** because the probability flow generated by $p_z p_y$ drives the system into the singularity of the $\\frac{1}{y}p_x$ term in finite time.",
